    "attributes": {
        "action": "Change the way Benefit Cap is applied.",
        "additional_details": "X is contracted to work, 2 x 8 hour shifts per week, with paid breaks.\r\nAs a single parent with 2 children and Social Housing Rent being \u00a3820.47 per month, they need to earn \u00a3569 not to be affected.\r\nIf only paid for 4 weeks, its \u00a3525.44 where as if 5, \u00a3656.80.\r\nOver 52 weeks, they have the required \u00a3569 on average. \r\nIf people have a contract of employment for 16 or more hours a week, they should be able to sent it in, and be exempt from the Cap.",
        "background": "To avoid Benefit Cap, you need to work for 16 hours in most cases. Where the issue exists, is when paid Weekly, every 2 weeks, 4 weekly or on a set day per month, for example last Friday.  Wage cut of days mean that you only have 4 weeks pay some months, so people get Benefit Capped",
